subaward_description:
SUBCONTRACTOR SHALL PERFORM THE FOLLOWING TASKS:
TASK 1: PROJECT MANAGEMENT
SUBTASK 1.3: ONGOING COMMUNICATIONS. AIR TASK LEADS WILL ATTEND PROJECT TELECONFERENCES WITH THE COR, AS REQUESTED BY THE PROJECT DIRECTOR. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL ALSO PREPARE INVOICES TO BE SUBMITTED BY THE 15TH OF EACH MONTH WITH BREAKOUTS BY TEAM MEMBERS FOR HOURS CHARGED BY SUBTASK. INVOICES WILL BE SUBMITTED BY THE 15TH OF THE MONTH AND BE ACCOMPANIED BY A MONTHLY MEMBERS DESCRIBING THE MONTHÃ¢Â‚¬Â„¢S PROJECT ACTIVITIES, ACCOMPLISHMENTS, RISKS OR ISSUES ENCOUNTERED, AND PROGRESS.
TASK 2: KNOWLEDGE DEVELOPMENT AND EVALUATION DESIGN OPTIONS
SUBTASK 2.1: KNOWLEDGE DEVELOPMENT. TO UNDERSTAND THE ES PROGRAM LANDSCAPE WHILE ALSO GATHERING INSIGHTS NECESSARY TO DEVELOP FEASIBLE AND RIGOROUS IMPACT DESIGN OPTION, THE STUDY TEAM WILL COMBINE DATA FROM MULTIPLE SOURCES TO CREATE AN INITIAL KNOWLEDGE DEVELOPMENT MEMO, WHICH WILL THEN INFORM DESIGN OPTIONS. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL:
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	SUPPORT DOCUMENT REVIEW
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	CONTRIBUTE TO/REVIEW GUIDES FOR IMPACT FEASIBILITY CALLS AND VISITS 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	CONDUCT FOUR (4) TWO-PERSON FEASIBILITY PHONE INTERVIEWS WITH STATES (WE ARE ASSUMING A TOTAL OF 20 STATE CALLS TO SELECT 12 FOR THE IMPACT STUDY)
SUBTASK 2.2: EVALUATION DESIGN OPTIONS REPORT. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL REVIEW AND PROVIDE FEEDBACK ON THE DESIGN OPTIONS MEMO.
SUBTASK 2.3: STATE RECRUITMENT AND SELECTION. AFTER THE COR APPROVES THE STATE RECRUITMENT AND SELECTION PLAN, THE STUDY TEAM WILL CONDUCT INITIAL CALLS WITH STATES. AFTER INITIAL CALLS THE TEAM WILL CONDUCT FOLLOW-UP CALLS WITH SITES THAT ARE DEEMED AS WELL SUITED TO THE EVALUATION. IF IT WOULD BE VALUABLE FOR PARTNERSHIP BUILDING, WE WILL CONSIDER CONDUCTING EVALUATION FEASIBILITY AND RECRUITMENT SITE VISITS TO HIGH-PRIORITY LOCATIONS, PRIORITIZING NON-WAIVER STATES SINCE THEY ARE NOT MANDATED TO PARTICIPATE IN THE EVALUATION. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL PROVIDE SUPPORT FOR THE RECRUITMENT AND DEVELOPMENT OF MEMORANDA OF UNDERSTANDING WITH FOUR STATES; MATHEMATICA LEADING.
TASK 3 IMPACT OUR OUTCOMES STUDY 
SUBTASK 3.1: IMPACT OR OUTCOME EVALUATION DESIGN REPORT. THE DESIGN REPORT WILL DESCRIBE THE IMPACT STUDY DESIGN, SAMPLE CREATION, SURVEY DATA COLLECTION, ADMINISTRATIVE DATA COLLECTION, ANALYSIS, AND REPORTING. THE DESIGN REPORT WILL DESCRIBE HOW THE IMPACT STUDY WILL BE INTEGRATED WITH THE IMPLEMENTATION STUDY TO DEFINE THE MODELS BEING EVALUATED AND PROVIDE CONTEXT FOR FINDINGS. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL CONTRIBUTE TO BRAINSTORMING AND REVIEW OF THE DESIGN REPORT.
SUBTASK 3.2. DATA COLLECTION INSTRUMENT DEVELOPMENT AND OFFICE OF MANAGEMENT AND BUDGET (OMB) PAPERWORK REDUCTION ACT (PRA) CLEARANCE FOR IMPACT OR OUTCOME STUDY. THE IMPACT STUDY WILL RELY ON A SURVEY OF LWDBS IN THE SELECTED SITES TO MEASURE ES STAFFING MODELS, SERVICE APPROACHES, AND OTHER PROGRAM FACTORS. THIS SURVEY WILL ALSO BE ESSENTIAL FOR THE IMPLEMENTATION STUDY. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL CONTRIBUTE TO BRAINSTORMING DURING THE DEVELOPMENT OF INSTRUMENTS AND REVIEW THEM. 
SUBTASK 3.3. DATA COLLECTION FOR IMPACT OR OUTCOME STUDY. THE IMPACT ANALYSIS WILL RELY ON SURVEY AND ADMINISTRATIVE DATA SOURCES TO PROVIDE INFORMATION ON (1) CHARACTERISTICS OF AJCS AND THEIR STAFFING MODELS AND (2) INFORMATION ON ES PARTICIPANTS INCLUDING SERVICE RECEIPT AND EMPLOYMENT OUTCOMES. IN ADDITION TO THESE SOURCES, WE WILL USE THE ACS TO MEASURE CHARACTERISTICS OF THE LOCAL AREA AND LABOR MARKET. WE WILL THEREFORE RELY PRIMARILY ON ADMINISTRATIVE DATA SOURCES, SUCH AS THE FOLLOWING: (1) WIPS: (2) STATE-LEVEL REPORTING SYSTEM DATA; (3) THE NDNH; AND (4) AGGREGATE PERFORMANCE REPORTING DATA.
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	AIR WILL SUPPORT COLLECTION AND CLEANING OF STATE AND LOCAL ADMINISTRATIVE DATA (LEADING IN 4 OF 12 STATES). 
SUBTASK 3.4. DATA ANALYSIS FOR IMPACT OR OUTCOME STUDY. THE STUDY TEAM WILL BUILD ON THE EVALUATION DESIGN REPORT AND SUBMIT A DETAILED ANALYSIS PLAN TO THE COR. Ã¯Â€ŠÂ§	CONTRIBUTE TO DEVELOPMENT OF KNOWLEDGE DEVELOPMENT MEMO
SUBTASK 2.2: EVALUATION DESIGN OPTIONS REPORT. THE REPORT WILL BEGIN WITH A CONCEPTUAL MODEL AND DESCRIBE OPTIONS TO ESTIMATE THE EFFECTS OF ES STAFFING MODELS, SITE-SPECIFIC FACTORS, AND APPROACHES USED TO PROVIDE SERVICES ON PARTICIPANTSÃ¢Â‚¬Â„¢ EMPLOYMENT, EARNINGS, ENROLLMENT IN AND COMPLETION OF TRAINING PROGRAMS, AND CO-ENROLLMENT IN OTHER WIOA PROGRAMS. IT WILL ALSO PROVIDE OPTIONS FOR AN OUTCOMES STUDY THAT CAREFULLY EXAMINES VARIATION IN THESE OUTCOMES. THE REPORT WILL PRESENT THE ADVANTAGES AND DISADVANTAGES OF THE OPTIONS BASED ON CRITERIA AND PRIORITIES DISCUSSED WITH DOL. FOR EACH OPTION, THE REPORT WILL PRESENT THE ASSOCIATED RESEARCH QUESTIONS, EXISTING LITERATURE, PROPOSED RESEARCH DESIGN, REQUIRED DATA AND ANALYSIS, AND REQUIRED TIME AND RESOURCES. 
THE REPORT WILL CONSIDER A RANGE OF POTENTIAL DESIGN METHODS, FOCUSING ON QEDS WITH DESIGNS THAT EXAMINE VARIATION IN STAFFING MODELS AT THE STATE AND LOCAL AREA LEVEL. IT WILL HIGHLIGHT THE DESIGN OPTIONS THAT ARE MOST APPLICABLE TO DIFFERENT RESEARCH QUESTIONS AND PROVIDE THE MOST RIGOROUS EVIDENCE. WHILE MANY STATISTICAL METHODOLOGIES WILL BE CONSIDERED, THESE METHODS ARE ALL BASED ON A COMPARISON OF PARTICIPANT OUTCOMES IN WAIVER STATES TO PARTICIPANT OUTCOMES IN NON-WAIVER STATES. THESE DESIGNS WOULD DRAW ON DATA FROM WORKFORCE INTEGRATED PERFORMANCE SYSTEM (WIPS) AND NATIONAL DIRECTORY OF NEW HIRES (NDNH) FOR PARTICIPANT OUTCOMES AND THE ACS TO IDENTIFY COMPARISON STATES OR SITES. 
Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	MEF WILL LEAD THE EVALUATION DESIGN OPTIONS REPORT.

AFTER INITIAL CALLS THE TEAM WILL CONDUCT FOLLOW-UP CALLS WITH SITES THAT ARE DEEMED AS WELL SUITED TO THE EVALUATION. Ã¢Â‚¬Â¢	MEF WILL CONTRIBUTE TO RECRUITMENT AND DEVELOPMENT OF MOUS WITH STATES; MATHEMATICA LEADING
